From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jerome Laban <noreply@platform.uno>
Date: Mon, 11 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fix: emit gsharedvt_out_sig wrappers symmetrically in
 LLVMOnly+Interp profile-guided AOT

In LLVMOnly+Interp mode (the WASM worker scenario), the AOT compiler
emits gsharedvt wrappers from three llvm_only paths in compile_method:

  1. cfg->method's own signature           -> OUT only
  2. cfg->signatures loop                   -> IN only  (historical)
  3. cfg->interp_in_signatures loop         -> IN only  (historical)

That asymmetry breaks the interp -> AOT direction. When the interpreter
calls into an AOT'd method whose codegen is gsharedvt-shared, it needs
a gsharedvt_out_sig wrapper for the call signature so init_jit_call_info
(mono/mini/interp/interp.c) can splice the call. If the OUT wrapper is
missing, mono_jit_compile_method_jit_only returns
  "Attempting to JIT compile method '(wrapper other) ... gsharedvt_out_sig ...'
   while running in aot-only mode"
and mono_error_assert_ok aborts the runtime.

Concrete repro from a WASM worker hosting Roslyn (.NET 10):

  [MONO] * Assertion at .../interp/interp.c, function: init_jit_call_info,
    Attempting to JIT compile method '(wrapper other) void object:
      gsharedvt_out_sig (intptr,
        Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CompoundUseSiteInfo`1<object>&,
        object&, object&, intptr)'
    while running in aot-only mode.

Empirically the missing CompoundUseSiteInfo OUT wrapper arrives at the
AOT image via cfg->interp_in_signatures (interp-entry registration for
AOT -> interp calls), NOT via cfg->signatures of any compiled method.
The IN-only emission in path 3 is therefore the load-bearing gap; path 2
was patched first (and is left in place because OUT coverage there is
also strictly needed in symmetric scenarios) but did not by itself close
the assertion.

This patch widens both paths to emit IN + OUT for the standard
(param_count <= MAX_INTERP_ENTRY_ARGS) branch. The large-arg-count
branch is left unchanged: it uses an interp_in wrapper and bypasses
gsharedvt entirely.

Trade-offs:
- Slightly larger AOT image (additional small "(wrapper other)" stubs
  per signature). Worker corpus: ~226 extra OUT wrappers, image grew
  from ~15,478 to ~15,704 gsharedvt_out_sig symbols, no measurable
  size change at the wasm output level.
- No runtime cost: wrappers are emitted statically; only invoked when
  the call site needs them.

Fixes: downstream WASM worker AOT path (LLVMOnly+Interp).
---
 src/mono/mono/mini/aot-compiler.c | 38 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++---
 1 file changed, 35 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/mono/mono/mini/aot-compiler.c b/src/mono/mono/mini/aot-compiler.c
index 8e9cdc6120f..efc7b353f81 100644
--- a/src/mono/mono/mini/aot-compiler.c
+++ b/src/mono/mono/mini/aot-compiler.c
@@ -9744,8 +9744,31 @@ compile_method (MonoAotCompile *acfg, MonoMethod *method)
 		for (l = cfg->signatures; l; l = l->next) {
 			MonoMethodSignature *sig = mono_metadata_signature_dup ((MonoMethodSignature*)l->data);

-			/* These only need in wrappers */
-			add_gsharedvt_wrappers (acfg, sig, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE);
+			/*
+			 * Emit both gsharedvt_in and gsharedvt_out wrappers for indirect-call
+			 * signatures observed during method compilation.
+			 *
+			 * Historically only gsharedvt_in was emitted here, on the assumption that
+			 * gsharedvt_out coverage from cfg->method's own signature (above) was
+			 * sufficient. That assumption breaks in LLVMOnly+Interp (profile-guided
+			 * AOT) when a generic method instantiation is reached only via the
+			 * interpreter side: the AOT compiler observes the signature in
+			 * cfg->signatures of some other method (indirect call through rgctx
+			 * ftndesc, delegate.Invoke, etc.) but never compiles a method whose
+			 * cfg->method signature matches, so no gsharedvt_out_sig wrapper is
+			 * emitted. The interpreter then asserts in init_jit_call_info
+			 * (interp/interp.c) when calling into the AOT'd target, because
+			 * mono_jit_compile_method_jit_only on the wrapper returns the
+			 * "Attempting to JIT compile method ... while running in aot-only mode"
+			 * error.
+			 *
+			 * Concrete repro from a WASM worker hosting Roslyn (.NET 10):
+			 *   gsharedvt_out_sig (intptr, Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CompoundUseSiteInfo`1<object>&,
+			 *                      object&, object&, intptr)
+			 * The same signature already gets a gsharedvt_in wrapper from this loop;
+			 * emitting the out wrapper symmetrically closes the gap.
+			 */
+			add_gsharedvt_wrappers (acfg, sig, TRUE, TRUE, FALSE);
 			if (mono_aot_mode_is_interp (&acfg->aot_opts) && sig->param_count > MAX_INTERP_ENTRY_ARGS)
 				/* See below */
 				add_gsharedvt_wrappers (acfg, sig, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE);
@@ -9759,11 +9782,22 @@ compile_method (MonoAotCompile *acfg, MonoMethod *method)
 			 * since we already generate those in llvmonly mode. But methods with a large
 			 * number of arguments need special processing (see interp_create_method_pointer_llvmonly),
 			 * which only interp_in wrappers do.
+			 *
+			 * Emit gsharedvt_out wrappers symmetrically: the same signature is exercised in the
+			 * opposite direction (interpreter calling an AOT'd method, init_jit_call_info in
+			 * interp/interp.c) when the AOT'd target uses gsharedvt-shared codegen. If the OUT
+			 * wrapper is missing the interpreter asserts with
+			 *   "Attempting to JIT compile method '(wrapper other) ... gsharedvt_out_sig ...'
+			 *    while running in aot-only mode."
+			 * The cfg->signatures loop above (which already emits both directions) does NOT
+			 * always cover these signatures — Roslyn's CompoundUseSiteInfo`1<object> appears in
+			 * cfg->interp_in_signatures via interp-entry registration without going through
+			 * cfg->signatures of any compiled method.
 			 */
 			if (sig->param_count > MAX_INTERP_ENTRY_ARGS)
 				add_gsharedvt_wrappers (acfg, sig, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE);
 			else
-				add_gsharedvt_wrappers (acfg, sig, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE);
+				add_gsharedvt_wrappers (acfg, sig, TRUE, TRUE, FALSE);
 		}
 	} else if (mono_aot_mode_is_full (&acfg->aot_opts) && mono_aot_mode_is_interp (&acfg->aot_opts)) {
 		/* The interpreter uses these wrappers to call aot-ed code */
--
